{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958625,"nonce":"78gB/P3MkAFLLtzStx4AsMHY334=","kind":"spec","title":"`kref show` rendering, pager, and content-type — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958625,"nonce":"KvgdAYhhDlVi5Y/xVXt60Gb7iAs=","body":"# `kref show` rendering, pager, and content-type — design\n\nDate: 2026-06-28\nStatus: approved (pending implementation plan)\n\n## Problem\n\n`kref show` writes a metadata header plus the stored body verbatim, straight to\nstdout. Two gaps:\n\n1. **No pager.** Long entries scroll off the terminal; there is no scroll,\n   search, or in-place navigation.\n2. **No rich rendering.** Bodies are markdown but print as raw markdown source.\n   There is no \"nice\" rendered view, and the entry model has no notion of what\n   *kind* of text a body is, so it could not render anything other than\n   markdown even if it wanted to.\n\n`update` must also be able to change an entry's content-type.\n\n## Scope and non-goals\n\n- **Text only.** Binary uploads (images, PDFs, octet-stream) are explicitly\n  disallowed and rejected at ingest/add/update. Rationale: bodies flow through\n  secret scanning, `kref diff`, concurrent-edit auto-merge, body-version\n  recovery, and `--json` (which serializes the body as a JSON string). All of\n  those assume UTF-8 text. A terminal cannot render binary anyway.\n- **No new internal-metadata mechanism.** content-type is a single-valued\n  intrinsic property (the same shape as `Kind`), so it gets a dedicated field,\n  not a reserved-prefix label. A general reserved-label internal-metadata\n  facility may be worth it later, but is a separate decision and is not\n  bootstrapped here.\n- **No `list` column for content-type** in this change (trivial to add later via\n  the existing column registry; out of scope unless requested).\n\n## Decisions (resolved during brainstorming)\n\n| Question | Decision |\n|---|---|\n| Content universe | Text only; reject binary / invalid UTF-8, fail-closed. |\n| Render richness | Markdown → glamour; code/structured text → chroma highlighting; plain → verbatim. |\n| Pager | Built-in TUI pager (bubbletea + bubbles `viewport`), full features. |\n| `--raw` vs `--no-header` | Orthogonal flags. `--raw` = verbatim body instead of rendered; `--no-header` = drop the metadata block. |\n| Pager gate | Interactive TTY \u0026\u0026 not `--json` \u0026\u0026 not `--no-pager`; independent of `--raw`/`--no-header`. |\n| content-type storage | Dedicated field on the op-log (`Create` + new `SetContentType`), default `text/markdown`. |\n| ingest scope | Detect content-type per file; markdown keeps trailer + tracking; non-markdown is content-only (no trailer, not tracked). |\n\n## Architecture\n\nThe existing seam is preserved: `internal/render` stays writer-based and\nunit-testable; `cmd/kref` owns IO policy (TTY detection, `--json`, and now the\npager). Detection/validation lives in a new pure `internal/content` package so\n`entry`/`bridge` can validate without importing any renderer.\n\n```\ninternal/content   pure: Detect(path,body), Canonical(ct), Lexer(ct), text/binary guard\ninternal/entry     ContentType field + Create.ContentType + SetContentType op\ninternal/store     Add(...contentType), SetContentType(id, ct)\ninternal/render    ShowHeader(...), RenderBody(w, body, contentType, color)  [glamour/chroma]\ncmd/kref/pager.go  bubbletea/viewport TUI pager (not pure; not in render)\ncmd/kref           show/add/update/ingest wiring; decides page vs. direct write\n```\n\n### 1. `internal/content` (new, pure, stdlib + chroma lexer names only)\n\n- `Detect(path string, body []byte) (string, error)`\n  - Binary guard first: error if `!utf8.Valid(body)` or body contains a NUL byte.\n  - Extension map: `.md`/`.markdown` → `text/markdown`, `.json` →\n    `application/json`, `.yaml`/`.yml` → `application/yaml`, `.toml` →\n    `application/toml`, `.go` → `text/x-go`, `.py` → `text/x-python`, `.sh` →\n    `text/x-shellscript`, `.js` → `text/javascript`, `.ts` → `text/x-typescript`,\n    plus a few common ones; unknown-but-text → `text/plain`.\n- `Canonical(ct string) (string, error)` — trims/normalizes, rejects any\n  non-text type (`image/*`, `application/octet-stream`, etc.). Used by\n  `add`/`update` flag validation and by `SetContentType.Validate`.\n- `Lexer(ct string) string` — content-type → chroma lexer name (empty = no\n  highlight, render verbatim).\n- `IsMarkdown(ct string) bool` — convenience for the trailer/tracking decision.\n\nThe single source of truth for the supported type set is a table in this\npackage, covered by a registry-consistency test (mirrors the existing column\nregistry pattern).\n\n### 2. `internal/entry`\n\n- `Snapshot.ContentType` — a `string` field tagged `json:\"content_type\"`. Empty\n  compiles to `text/markdown` (back-compat: ops authored before this field omit\n  it and deserialize to the empty string).\n- `Create` op gains a `ContentType` string field (`json:\"content_type\"`);\n  `Apply` sets it (default applied when empty).\n- New `SetContentType` op, structurally identical to `SetKind`:\n  - `NewSetContentType(author, ct)`.\n  - `Validate` → non-empty and `content.Canonical` accepts it (text only).\n  - `Apply(s)` → `s.ContentType = op.ContentType; s.UpdatedAt = op.Time()`.\n- `history.go`: add `set-content-type` to the op-string list and a `detail`\n  summary (the new content-type).\n\n### 3. `internal/store`\n\n- Create path carries content-type. `Store.Add` has ~60 existing callers\n  (mostly tests), so rather than churn its signature, add\n  `AddWithContentType(t, kind, title, body, contentType)` carrying the full\n  create, and keep `Add` as a thin delegate that passes the `text/markdown`\n  default. Only the two callers that need a non-default type — the `add`\n  command and the ingest create path — call the new method; existing callers\n  are untouched. (`Add` retains 60+ callers, so it is not a trivial wrapper\n  under the codebase's extract rule.)\n- `SetContentType(id entity.Id, ct string) error` — opens the entry, appends a\n  `SetContentType` op, commits. Mirrors `SetKind`.\n\n### 4. `internal/render`\n\n- Keep `Tier`, list rendering, `Action`, `Log`, `BodyVersions` unchanged.\n- Split `Show`:\n  - `ShowHeader(w, snap, color)` — the existing metadata block (id, `[tier/status]`,\n    title, author, labels, merged line, provenance, tracked line).\n  - `RenderBody(w io.Writer, body, contentType string, color bool)`:\n    - `text/markdown` → glamour. Style: auto/dark when `color`, ASCII/notty\n      when not (keeps piped and test output plain and deterministic).\n    - `content.Lexer(ct) != \"\"` → chroma. Terminal formatter when `color`,\n      no-color formatter otherwise.\n    - else → verbatim copy.\n- `Show` is reimplemented in terms of the two, preserving current default output\n  byte-for-byte when content-type is markdown and color is off, except the body\n  is now rendered (the header is unchanged).\n\nRendering targets an `io.Writer`, so glamour/chroma output is unit-tested with\n`color=false`.\n\n### 5. `cmd/kref` — pager and wiring\n\n`pager.go` (new): a bubbletea program wrapping bubbles `viewport`.\n\n- Scroll: `j`/`k`, arrows, `ctrl-d`/`ctrl-u`, `PgUp`/`PgDn`, `g`/`G`\n  (top/bottom), mouse wheel.\n- Search: `/` to enter a query, `n`/`N` for next/previous match, matches\n  highlighted.\n- Status bar: entry id + title, scroll percentage, line position.\n- Help: `?` toggles a keybinding overlay.\n- Quit: `q` / `Esc`.\n\nThe pager receives a **pre-rendered string** (header + body, already produced by\n`render`), so it is pure presentation/navigation — no entry logic inside the TUI.\n\n`show` command flow:\n\n1. Resolve target (existing `resolveTargetOrRecent`), `s.Get`, merged/drift as today.\n2. Build the output string via `render` honoring `--raw` (verbatim body) and\n   `--no-header` (omit header block).\n3. If `--json` → existing JSON path; snapshot now includes `content_type`.\n4. Else if `term.IsTerminal(stdout)` \u0026\u0026 `!--no-pager` → run the pager with the string.\n5. Else → write the string to stdout (current behavior).\n\nNew flags:\n\n- `show`: `--raw`, `--no-header`, `--no-pager`.\n- `add`: `--content-type` (default empty → `text/markdown`), validated via\n  `content.Canonical`.\n- `update`: `--content-type`, single and bulk (same category as `--kind`).\n  Body source (`--file`/`--body`/stdin) is independent; content-type changes\n  only via the explicit flag. Validated via `content.Canonical`.\n- `ingest`: per-file detection. Markdown → unchanged (trailer + tracking).\n  Non-markdown text → content-only: store body + detected content-type, record\n  origin, **no trailer write-back, not file-tracked**. Binary/invalid-UTF-8 →\n  per-file error reported in the ingest summary (beside the secret-scan errors).\n  Summary line shows the detected type for non-markdown files.\n\n## Color / TTY semantics\n\nReuse the existing `useColor` gate. `color=true` only for human output to an\ninteractive terminal with `NO_COLOR` unset. Renderers map `color` to glamour's\nstyled-vs-notty style and chroma's terminal-vs-no-color formatter, so piped and\n`go test` output is plain and deterministic — consistent with the current\ncolor behavior.\n\n## Dependencies\n\nNew direct, MIT-licensed, pinned (`go mod tidy`, commit `go.sum`):\n\n- `github.com/charmbracelet/glamour` — markdown rendering.\n- `github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea` — TUI runtime.\n- `github.com/charmbracelet/bubbles` — `viewport` pager component.\n- `github.com/charmbracelet/lipgloss` — styling (also transitive via glamour/bubbles).\n- `github.com/alecthomas/chroma/v2` — syntax highlighting (also transitive via glamour).\n\nThis is the standard, widely-used Go TUI stack (glow, `gh`). It is a real\nfootprint increase, accepted as an explicit decision in favor of the full\nin-process pager experience.\n\n## Testing\n\nArtifacts to `.test-output/` (gitignored); human and LLM modes via the Taskfile.\n\n- `internal/content`: extension → content-type mapping; `Canonical` accepts\n  text and rejects binary types; `Detect` rejects invalid UTF-8 / NUL; registry\n  consistency (every supported type has a lexer decision).\n- `internal/entry`: `SetContentType` apply/validate; `Create` default; empty\n  field back-compat → `text/markdown`.\n- `internal/render`: `RenderBody` per content-type (markdown rendered, code\n  highlighted under color, plain verbatim); `--raw` bypasses rendering;\n  `--no-header` omits the header; default markdown output unchanged with color off.\n- `internal/bridge`: non-markdown ingest is content-only (no trailer, not\n  tracked); binary file rejected; extension → content-type.\n- `cmd/kref`: `show --raw`/`--no-header`; `--json` includes `content_type`;\n  `add --content-type`; `update --content-type` single and bulk; validation\n  errors for binary content-types.\n- `pager`: bubbletea `teatest` — scroll, search, quit; the render path is\n  unit-tested independently of the TUI.\n\nNegative cases throughout: binary rejection, invalid content-type, empty\ncontent-type, `update --content-type` in bulk vs. per-entry content flags.\n\n## Documentation\n\n- README: `show` (`--raw`, `--no-header`, `--no-pager`, pager keybindings),\n  `add`/`update` (`--content-type`), `ingest` (non-markdown content-only behavior).\n- CHANGELOG entry.\n- JSON contract note: `show`/`list` snapshots gain `content_type`.\n\n## Backward compatibility\n\n- Existing entries (no `content_type` in their ops) render as `text/markdown` —\n  the prior behavior, now rendered instead of raw.\n- `--json` gains an additive field; existing consumers are unaffected.\n- Default `show` header is unchanged; only the body presentation changes (and\n  `--raw` recovers the exact prior bytes)."}]}